            <li><strong>30 Days Later:</strong> General check-in and seasonal tips</li>
            <li><strong>90 Days Later:</strong> Seasonal service reminder</li>
            <li><strong>6 Months Later:</strong> Maintenance schedule reminder</li>
            <li><strong>12 Months Later:</strong> Annual service anniversary message</li>
          </ol>
        </div>
      </div>

      <h2 id="measuring-success">Measuring Retention Success</h2>

      <div class="prose prose-blue max-w-none">
        <p>Retention measurement requires both leading and lagging indicators. Lagging indicators like annual retention rates show historical performance but don't predict future trends. Leading indicators like maintenance agreement renewals, communication response rates, and service satisfaction scores predict future retention.</p>

        <p>Calculate retention rates quarterly to identify trends before they impact annual results. Use the formula: (Customers at End of Period - New Customers) / Customers at Start of Period × 100. Segment retention by customer type (maintenance vs. service-only) and acquisition source for deeper insights.</p>

        <p>Customer satisfaction scores predict retention 6-12 months in advance. Customers rating their experience 9-10 have 95% retention rates. Customers rating 7-8 have 60% retention. Customers rating below 7 have 25% retention. This makes satisfaction tracking a critical early warning system.</p>

        <p>Revenue per customer trends indicate retention health. Declining average revenue per customer often signals reduced service frequency or competitor switching. Increasing revenue per customer suggests successful upselling and stronger relationships.</p>

        <p>Track these metrics in your CRM dashboard for monthly review. Companies that review retention metrics monthly identify problems 3-4 months earlier than those reviewing annually, allowing for proactive intervention before customers leave.</p>
      </div>

